readme.md
    20â†’## Benefits over plain `fetch`
    22â†’- Simpler API
    23â†’- Method shortcuts (`ky.post()`)
    24â†’- Treats non-2xx status codes as errors (after redirects)
    25â†’- Retries failed requests
    26â†’- JSON option
    27â†’- Timeout support
    28â†’- URL prefix option
    29â†’- Instances with custom defaults
    30â†’- Hooks
    31â†’- TypeScript niceties (e.g. `.json()` supports generics and defaults to `unknown`, not `any`)
    32â†’
    33â†’## Install
    35â†’```sh
    36â†’npm install ky
    37â†’```
    38â†’
    39â†’###### CDN
    41â†’- [jsdelivr](https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/ky/+esm)
    42â†’- [unpkg](https://unpkg.com/ky)
    43â†’- [esm.sh](https://esm.sh/ky)
      â†’â€¦
    45â†’## Usage
    47â†’```js
    48â†’import ky from 'ky';
    49â†’
    50â†’const json = await ky.post('https://example.com', {json: {foo: true}}).json();
    51â†’
    52â†’console.log(json);
    53â†’//=> {data: 'đź¦„'}
    54â†’```
    55â†’
    56â†’With plain `fetch`, it would be:
    57â†’
    58â†’```js
    59â†’class HTTPError extends Error {}
    60â†’
    61â†’const response = await fetch('https://example.com', {
    62â†’	method: 'POST',
    63â†’	body: JSON.stringify({foo: true}),
    64â†’	headers: {
    65â†’		'content-type': 'application/json'
    66â†’	}
    67â†’});
    68â†’
    69â†’if (!response.ok) {
    70â†’	throw new HTTPError(`Fetch error: ${response.statusText}`);
    71â†’}
    72â†’
    73â†’const json = await response.json();
    74â†’
    75â†’console.log(json);
    76â†’//=> {data: 'đź¦„'}
    77â†’```
    78â†’
    79â†’If you are using [Deno](https://github.com/denoland/deno), import Ky from a URL. For example, using a CDN:
    80â†’
    81â†’```js
    82â†’import ky from 'https://esm.sh/ky';
    83â†’```
    84â†’
    85â†’## API
    87â†’### ky(input, options?)
    89â†’The `input` and `options` are the same as [`fetch`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WindowOrWorkerGlobalScope/fetch), with additional `options` available (see below).
    90â†’
    91â†’Returns a [`Response` object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Response) with [`Body` methods](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Fetch_API/Using_Fetch#body) added for convenience. So you can, for example, call `ky.get(input).json()` directly without having to await the `Response` first. When called like that, an appropriate `Accept` header will be set depending on the body method used. Unlike the `Body` methods of `window.Fetch`, these will throw an `HTTPError` if the response status is not in the range of `200...299`. Also, `.json()` will return an empty string if body is empty or the response status is `204` instead of throwing a parse error due to an empty body.
    92â†’
    93â†’Available body shortcuts: `.json()`, `.text()`, `.formData()`, `.arrayBuffer()`, `.blob()`, and `.bytes()`. The `.bytes()` shortcut is only present when the runtime supports `Response.prototype.bytes()`.
    94â†’
    95â†’```js
    96â†’import ky from 'ky';
    97â†’
    98â†’const user = await ky('/api/user').json();
    99â†’
   100â†’console.log(user);
   101â†’```
   102â†’
   103â†’âŚ¨ď¸Ź **TypeScript:** Accepts an optional [type parameter](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/generics.html), which defaults to [`unknown`](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/functions.html#unknown), and is passed through to the return type of `.json()`.
   104â†’
   105â†’```ts
   106â†’import ky from 'ky';
   107â†’
   108â†’// user1 is unknown
   109â†’const user1 = await ky('/api/users/1').json();
   110â†’// user2 is a User
   111â†’const user2 = await ky<User>('/api/users/2').json();
   112â†’// user3 is a User
   113â†’const user3 = await ky('/api/users/3').json<User>();
   114â†’
   115â†’console.log([user1, user2, user3]);
   116â†’
   117â†’// Get raw bytes (when supported by the runtime)
   118â†’const bytes = await ky('/api/file').bytes();
   119â†’console.log(bytes instanceof Uint8Array);
   120â†’```
   121â†’
